description:
I've been developing a jface text plugin, and in that plugin I contribute a format action to the edit 
menu.  With all 3.0 stream builds before the 20030924 nightly build, my contributed format action 
works fine.  With all builds including and after the 20030924 nightly build, clicking on the format 
action in the edit menu in my plugin does not envoke my IFormattingStrategy methods.  For more 
detail please see below.


__________________________
public class XMLConfiguration extends SourceViewerConfiguration
{ ...
    public IContentFormatter getContentFormatter(ISourceViewer sourceViewer)
    {
        System.out.println("XMLConfiguration:getContentFormatter");
        ContentFormatter formatter = new ContentFormatter();
        formatter.setDocumentPartitioning(
                    getConfiguredDocumentPartitioning(sourceViewer));
        formatter.enablePartitionAwareFormatting(false);
        formatter.setFormattingStrategy(new GarbageFormattingStrategy(), 
IDocument.DEFAULT_CONTENT_TYPE);
        return formatter;
    }

__________________________
public class GarbageFormattingStrategy implements IFormattingStrategy
{
    public void formatterStarts(String initialIndentation)
    {
        System.out.println("GarbageFormattingStrategy:formatterStarts");
    }

    public String format(
        String content,
        boolean isLineStart,
        String indentation,
        int[] positions)
    {
        System.out.println("GarbageFormattingStrategy:format");
        return "test";
    }

    public void formatterStops()
    {
        System.out.println("GarbageFormattingStrategy:formatterStops");
    }
}
__________________________

This code run in the Run-time workbench in builds before 20030924 produces the following in the 
console after clicking edit -> format within my plugin's context:

XMLConfiguration:getContentFormatter
GarbageFormattingStrategy:formatterStarts
GarbageFormattingStrategy:format
GarbageFormattingStrategy:formatterStops

This code run in the Run-time workbench in build 20030924 and all subsequent builds produces 
the following in the console after clicking edit -> format within my plugin's context:

XMLConfiguration:getContentFormatter

Build 200310230800

DOC PROBLEM:

The FileDialog(Shell) method documentation indicates that null can be passed in 
as the Shell parameter, which is not true.


INCONSISTENT API BEHAVIOR:

The following code acts differently on Windows vs. Linux Motif.  Run the code 
and cancel the dialog.  On Windows names is an empty array, on Linux it's null.

Note that the JUnit test case expects an empty array, so the JUnit test case 
fails on Linux-Motif.

import org.eclipse.swt.SWT;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.FileDialog;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Shell;

public class TestFileDialog {
	public static void main (String [] args) {
		Shell shell = new Shell();
		FileDialog fd = new FileDialog(shell, SWT.NULL);
		fd.open();
		String[] names = fd.getFileNames();
		if (names == null) System.out.println("null value");
		else System.out.println("non-null value");
	}	
}

Build 20031029

I was getting an NPE in AntCorePreferences#getURLs from the code that reads:
    IAntClasspathEntry entry = additionalEntries[i];
    result.add(entry.getEntryURL());

This was happening because the additionalEntries array contained a single 
element, which was null. The null element came from 
AntCorePreferences#restoreAdditionalEntries(Preferences):
    additionalEntries = new IAntClasspathEntry[]{getToolsJarEntry()};

The method getToolsJarEntry() can return null.

Since I upgraded from version 2.1.1 to version 3.0M4, I have been getting 
ClassCastExceptions intermittently, although I have found a way to reproduce 
it. The culprit is the 'isSynchronized' method of FileDocumentProvider in 
package org.eclipse.ui.editors.text:

	/*
	 * @see 
org.eclipse.ui.texteditor.IDocumentProviderExtension3#isSynchronized
(java.lang.Object)
	 * @since 3.0
	 */
	public boolean isSynchronized(Object element) {
		Object elementInfo= getElementInfo(element);
		if (elementInfo instanceof FileInfo) {
			FileEditorInput input= (FileEditorInput) element;
			IResource resource= input.getFile();
			return resource.isSynchronized(IResource.DEPTH_ZERO);
		}
		return false;
	}

That cast is not safe, why not use 'instanceof' on 'element' instead 
of 'elementInfo' to guard it properly? Why bother getting the 'element into', 
whatever that is, at all. It isn't used. Anyways, the solution that you guys 
might want is to cast 'element' to 'IFileEditorInput' instead 
of 'FileEditorInput'. I have my own editor input that is an 'IFileEditorInput' 
but not a 'FileEditorInput', and so I get a ClassCastException.

This would be my rewrite:

	public boolean isSynchronized(Object element) {
		if (element instanceof IFileEditorInput) {
			FileEditorInput input= (FileEditorInput) element;
			IResource resource= input.getFile();
			return resource.isSynchronized(IResource.DEPTH_ZERO);
		}
		return false;
	}
